    await _addFlashcards('itil-v4', 'module-2', [
      {'order': 1, 'question': 'What is a service offering?', 'answer': 'A service offering is a specific mix of services and products sold to a target customer group. It can include goods, access to resources, and service actions tailored to meet the needs of particular consumers.', 'example': 'A managed IT company might offer a Silver package (email + basic support) and a Gold package (full IT management + 24/7 helpdesk).'},
      {'order': 2, 'question': 'What is the difference between a service consumer and a service provider?', 'answer': 'A service provider creates and delivers services to generate value. A service consumer receives and uses those services. The consumer role can be split into customers (who define requirements), users (who use the service), and sponsors (who authorise budget).', 'example': 'A company that buys HR software is the customer; its employees using it daily are users; the CFO approving the purchase is the sponsor.'},
      {'order': 3, 'question': 'What is service relationship management?', 'answer': 'Service relationship management covers the joint activities performed by a service provider and service consumer to co-create value and continually improve service delivery. It includes service provision, consumption, and the ongoing relationship between both parties.', 'example': 'Regular service review meetings between a company and its IT outsourcer to discuss performance, improvements, and future needs.'},
      {'order': 4, 'question': 'What is utility in ITIL V4?', 'answer': 'Utility is the functionality offered by a product or service to meet a particular need — it is what the service does. A service has utility if it either supports the performance of a consumer or removes constraints from them.', 'example': 'A project management tool has utility because it helps teams track tasks, deadlines, and responsibilities more efficiently.'},
      {'order': 5, 'question': 'What is warranty in ITIL V4?', 'answer': 'Warranty refers to the assurance that a product or service will meet agreed requirements — it is how the service performs. Warranty is about availability, capacity, security, and continuity of the service.', 'example': 'A cloud provider guaranteeing 99.9% uptime and encrypted data storage is providing warranty alongside its service utility.'},
      {'order': 6, 'question': 'What is the difference between an outcome and an output?', 'answer': 'An output is a tangible or intangible deliverable produced by an activity — something measurable and concrete. An outcome is a result for a stakeholder enabled by one or more outputs — it is the actual change or benefit achieved.', 'example': 'Output: a new mobile app is deployed. Outcome: customers complete purchases 40% faster, increasing revenue.'},
    ]);

