      {'order': 1, 'question': 'What are the Four Dimensions of Service Management?', 'answer': 'The Four Dimensions are: 1) Organisations and People, 2) Information and Technology, 3) Partners and Suppliers, 4) Value Streams and Processes. Every service and practice must be considered through all four dimensions to be effective.', 'example': 'Launching a new IT service requires thinking about the team structure, the technology used, any third-party vendors, and the workflow processes involved.'},
      {'order': 2, 'question': 'What does the Organisations and People dimension cover?', 'answer': 'This dimension addresses roles, responsibilities, organisational structure, culture, and the skills and competencies needed to deliver services. It focuses on how people work together and whether the culture supports the goals of the organisation.', 'example': 'A company that encourages collaboration and continuous learning will deliver better IT services than one with siloed teams and poor communication.'},
      {'order': 3, 'question': 'What does the Information and Technology dimension cover?', 'answer': 'This dimension covers the information, knowledge, tools, and technologies needed to manage and deliver services. It includes IT systems, databases, communication systems, AI tools, and the data required to make decisions.', 'example': 'A service desk needs ticketing software, a knowledge base, and a communication platform to manage and resolve incidents effectively.'},
      {'order': 4, 'question': 'What does the Partners and Suppliers dimension cover?', 'answer': 'This dimension focuses on the relationships an organisation has with other businesses that support service delivery. It includes outsourcing partners, cloud vendors, software providers, and any third party whose products or services are used.', 'example': 'A company using AWS for hosting, Microsoft for productivity tools, and a local MSP for support is managing multiple partner and supplier relationships.'},
      {'order': 5, 'question': 'What does the Value Streams and Processes dimension cover?', 'answer': 'This dimension defines how the various parts of an organisation work together to create value. Value streams are the series of steps from demand to delivery of a service. Processes define the detailed activities, inputs, outputs, and roles within those steps.', 'example': 'The process for handling a service request goes from submission, through approval and fulfilment, to closure — each step adds value toward the final outcome.'},
      {'order': 6, 'question': 'What are the external factors that affect the Four Dimensions?', 'answer': 'The Four Dimensions are all influenced by external PESTLE factors: Political, Economic, Social, Technological, Legal, and Environmental. These factors are outside the organisation\'s control but significantly affect how services are designed and managed.', 'example': 'GDPR (a legal factor) forced many organisations to rethink their Information and Technology dimension to ensure data privacy compliance.'},
    ]);

    await _addQuiz('itil-v4', 'module-3', [
      {'order': 1, 'question': 'How many dimensions of service management does ITIL V4 define?', 'options': ['2', '3', '4', '5'], 'correctIndex': 2, 'explanation': 'ITIL V4 defines four dimensions: Organisations & People, Information & Technology, Partners & Suppliers, and Value Streams & Processes.'},
      {'order': 2, 'question': 'Which dimension focuses on culture, roles and skills?', 'options': ['Information and Technology', 'Organisations and People', 'Value Streams and Processes', 'Partners and Suppliers'], 'correctIndex': 1, 'explanation': 'The Organisations and People dimension addresses culture, structure, roles, responsibilities, and competencies.'},
      {'order': 3, 'question': 'A company using AWS for hosting falls under which dimension?', 'options': ['Organisations and People', 'Information and Technology', 'Partners and Suppliers', 'Value Streams and Processes'], 'correctIndex': 2, 'explanation': 'Third-party vendors like AWS fall under the Partners and Suppliers dimension.'},
      {'order': 4, 'question': 'What is a value stream?', 'options': ['A financial report on service ROI', 'A series of steps from demand to delivery of a service', 'A type of ITIL practice', 'A communication channel between teams'], 'correctIndex': 1, 'explanation': 'A value stream is the series of steps an organisation takes to create and deliver value to service consumers.'},
      {'order': 5, 'question': 'What does PESTLE stand for in the context of ITIL V4?', 'options': ['Process, Escalation, Service, Technology, Legal, Environment', 'Political, Economic, Social, Technological, Legal, Environmental', 'People, Events, Strategy, Timing, Learning, Evaluation', 'Practice, Efficiency, Service, Team, Leadership, Execution'], 'correctIndex': 1, 'explanation': 'PESTLE stands for Political, Economic, Social, Technological, Legal, Environmental — external factors influencing the four dimensions.'},
      {'order': 6, 'question': 'Why must all four dimensions be considered together?', 'options': ['To increase IT costs', 'Because neglecting any one dimension can cause services to fail or underperform', 'Because ITIL V4 requires it as a legal standard', 'Only large organisations need to consider all four'], 'correctIndex': 1, 'explanation': 'Neglecting any dimension creates an imbalance — effective service management requires all four to be addressed together.'},
    ]);

    // MODULE 4 - Service Value System
    await _addFlashcards('itil-v4', 'module-4', [
      {'order': 1, 'question': 'What is the Service Value System (SVS)?', 'answer': 'The SVS is ITIL V4\'s model showing how all components and activities of an organisation work together to enable value creation. It describes how demand and opportunity are converted into valuable outcomes through a connected set of elements.', 'example': 'Think of the SVS as the engine of ITIL — it shows how everything from leadership decisions to daily IT tasks connects to produce value for customers.'},
      {'order': 2, 'question': 'What are the five components of the SVS?', 'answer': 'The five components are: 1) Guiding Principles, 2) Governance, 3) Service Value Chain, 4) Practices, and 5) Continual Improvement. Together, these components enable flexible and coordinated value creation.', 'example': 'When a new service is launched, the guiding principles inform decisions, governance ensures oversight, the value chain handles delivery, practices provide methods, and continual improvement ensures it gets better over time.'},
      {'order': 3, 'question': 'What is the Service Value Chain?', 'answer': 'The Service Value Chain is an operating model within the SVS that outlines six activities needed to respond to demand and create value: Plan, Improve, Engage, Design and Transition, Obtain and Build, and Deliver and Support.', 'example': 'When a customer requests a new laptop, the chain activates: engage (take the request), obtain/build (procure device), deliver/support (set it up and hand it over).'},
      {'order': 4, 'question': 'What is the role of governance in the SVS?', 'answer': 'Governance ensures that the organisation is directed, evaluated, and monitored appropriately. It provides oversight to ensure that policies, objectives, and strategies are followed — balancing accountability with flexibility.', 'example': 'A board of directors sets IT security policies; governance ensures these are followed across all service delivery teams.'},
      {'order': 5, 'question': 'What is continual improvement in ITIL V4?', 'answer': 'Continual improvement is the ongoing effort to improve services, products, and practices across the organisation. It applies at all levels — from individual tasks to entire business strategies — using the Continual Improvement Model as a structured approach.', 'example': 'After reviewing helpdesk tickets, a team identifies that 30% relate to password resets and implements self-service password reset — that is continual improvement.'},
      {'order': 6, 'question': 'What inputs drive the SVS?', 'answer': 'The SVS is driven by two inputs: Opportunity and Demand. Opportunity refers to possibilities for adding value or improving existing services. Demand is the need for services or products from internal and external customers.', 'example': 'A business sees growing demand for mobile access to its systems (demand) and identifies an opportunity to launch a mobile app (opportunity).'},
    ]);

    await _addQuiz('itil-v4', 'module-4', [
      {'order': 1, 'question': 'What does the Service Value System describe?', 'options': ['How to write IT contracts', 'How all components of an organisation work together to enable value creation', 'The financial model for IT services', 'The org chart of an IT department'], 'correctIndex': 1, 'explanation': 'The SVS describes how all components and activities of an organisation work together to enable value creation.'},
      {'order': 2, 'question': 'How many components make up the SVS?', 'options': ['3', '4', '5', '6'], 'correctIndex': 2, 'explanation': 'The SVS has five components: Guiding Principles, Governance, Service Value Chain, Practices, and Continual Improvement.'},
      {'order': 3, 'question': 'Which SVS component is an operating model with six activities?', 'options': ['Governance', 'Continual Improvement', 'The Service Value Chain', 'Guiding Principles'], 'correctIndex': 2, 'explanation': 'The Service Value Chain is the operating model within the SVS with six activities: Plan, Improve, Engage, Design & Transition, Obtain & Build, Deliver & Support.'},
      {'order': 4, 'question': 'What are the two inputs to the SVS?', 'options': ['People and Technology', 'Demand and Opportunity', 'Strategy and Tactics', 'Costs and Benefits'], 'correctIndex': 1, 'explanation': 'The SVS is driven by Demand (need for services) and Opportunity (possibilities to add value).'},
      {'order': 5, 'question': 'What is the purpose of governance within the SVS?', 'options': ['To slow down service delivery', 'To replace management decisions', 'To direct, evaluate and monitor the organisation appropriately', 'To handle customer complaints'], 'correctIndex': 2, 'explanation': 'Governance provides oversight to ensure policies, objectives and strategies are followed across the organisation.'},
      {'order': 6, 'question': 'At which level does continual improvement apply?', 'options': ['Only at the management level', 'Only to failing services', 'At all levels — from individual tasks to business strategy', 'Only during major incidents'], 'correctIndex': 2, 'explanation': 'Continual improvement applies at every level of the organisation, from individual work practices to the overall business strategy.'},
